      "side": 1,
      "message": "hmm, you\u0027re correct it depends on how it\u0027s used\n\nthe intention was to pass it directly to the kernel and not attempt to parse it at all.  the program is in read-only (const) memory.  the kernel isn\u0027t going to read user memory directly, it copies the buffer to its own before manipulating it -- see seccomp_prepare_filter.\n\nhttps://chromium.googlesource.com/chromiumos/third_party/kernel/+/refs/tags/v5.10.71/kernel/seccomp.c#543\nhttps://chromium.googlesource.com/chromiumos/third_party/kernel/+/refs/tags/v5.10.71/net/core/filter.c#1391\n\ni\u0027ll note that the struct/buffer declared here doesn\u0027t include alignment, so if something attempts to cast it to stricter alignment before using it, it\u0027s arguably a bug in that thing :).  do you have any uses cases of where this would actually show up ?  afaik, mj isn\u0027t going to be parsing this buffer directly.\n\nthat said, adding an explicit 4-byte alignment attribute for the buffer is pretty trivial and cheap.",
